article.headline: Northwestern 50, North Florida 49
article.story: EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) -- Freshman Kevin Coble's jumper with 3.2 seconds left gave Northwestern a 40-39 win over North Florida Saturday. Coble was near the basket when Craig Moore went up for a three point shot from the left side. The shot tipped the rim and Coble was waiting for it. He grabbed the rebound, and shot the ball in from the right side. Tim Doyle led Northwestern (2-3) with eight points and six rebounds. Coble finished the night with six points and six rebounds. It was the lowest scoring game for the Wildcats since they beat Purdue on the road on February 11, 2004 by the same score. Chris Timberlake and Aaron Caruthers led all scorers with 10 points apiece, and Gallo Cham had a game high 10 rebounds as the Ospreys (1-5) outrebounded Northwestern 40-34. Moore finished with six points and seven rebounds. Both teams struggled from behind the arc. North Florida made just three of their 10 3-point attempts, while the Wildcats hit only four of 25 from 3-point range. Northwestern coach Bill Carmody acknowledged that his team could have played better. "Our freshmen played like freshmen and our upperclassmen played like freshmen," he said. "We had a lot of guys who looked like they had dead hands." The Ospreys led 20-19 at halftime. North Florida coach Matt Kilcullen said the Ospreys missed some key shots in the closing minutes of the game. "We have to do a better job in the last five minutes of the game," Kilcullen said. "We had some great shots that didn't fall. And we missed three of our last four free throws."
